post_text:
Hello,

We need your input for a proposed safety/trail project in your community!

The project includes a trail and protected street crossing beginning at the intersection of Pomona Street and Crockett Boulevard and continuing to the entrance of Willow High School and Crockett Hills Regional Park (see a map of the project here). This trail is needed to provide a safe route for students and the public to reach the bus and downtown Crockett.

Contra Costa County is working with John Swett Unified School District, the Bay Area Ridge Trail Council and East Bay Regional Park District to seek funding for the project through a State grant.

Please fill out the survey linked below by August 24th to provide your input on the project. Input from this survey will be submitted with the grant application.

Crockett Boulevard Trail Project Survey:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSevexpeuJPqSguhiiZ8m1ahFxUNmLDkygclEfC_f81fxC8mmg/viewform

UPDATES ABOUT THE CORONA VIRUS:

Based on new information from our County Health Department, along with the current trajectory of the pandemic, we will be advising our Governing Board that we begin the year in All Distance Learning mode with the intent to return to in-person/hybrid learning once things are safe enough to do so.

Information Portal in English and Spanish:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1TUTMbtO9ImozuWfpvcGPcm8tcJEQxjVuT7XpIPTiwlU/mobilebasic

ACTUALIZACIONES SOBRE EL VIRUS DE CORONA:

Según la nueva información del Departamento de Salud de nuestro Condado, junto con la trayectoria actual de la pandemia, informaremos a nuestra Junta de Gobierno que comencemos el año en el modo de Aprendizaje a Distancia con la intención de volver al aprendizaje en persona / híbrido una vez que las cosas son lo suficientemente seguros como para hacerlo.

Portal de información en inglés y español:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1TUTMbtO9ImozuWfpvcGPcm8tcJEQxjVuT7XpIPTiwlU/mobilebasic

As we prepare to re-open schools in the Fall, we recognize that some parents may not be prepared to send their children to school and will need an alternative to in-person learning. As such, we have developed a Distance Learning Academy that will allow a child to remain at home and still get access to a top-quality education. If you elect to enroll your child in the Distance Learning Academy, they can only return at the Semester or Trimester break, so choose this option carefully.

If you would like to enroll in our Distance Learning Academy, click the link below.

Crockett, CA Library
July 1 at 2:00 PM ·

Cheerleading Workshop with California Spirit Elite
Wednesday, July 8 @ 12-1pm (PST)

California Spirit Elite is putting on a live online cheerleading workshop geared for 5-10 year olds! They will teach us a cheer and a short dance. Let's cheer for summer!

Sponsored by the Danville Library Endowment

To access this event you will need to register at: https://ccclib.bibliocommons.com/events/search/q=spirit%20elite/event/5ed6a769952c682400795ccc

We will email you the “Join Zoom Meeting” link and password a couple of days before the performance. You will be stepped through a short process to download and use a Zoom program that will enable you to see the event live. NOTE: If you already have Zoom installed, DO NOT open it first, just click on the Zoom Meeting link you will receive.

You can also view the recorded video the next day on Facebook at www.facebook.com/ccclib or YouTube at www.youtube.com/user/theccclibor the Danville Library Instagram account later for a link to the recording of the live show in case you missed it!

Rodeo Hills Elementary
June 17 at 12:42 PM ·

Here is a message from Lifetouch about our school yearbooks:

Lifetouch is currently on a journey to provide a World Class experience for you, as a valued yearbook customer. It has been our pleasure to partner with your school on this year’s yearbook and we know how important yearbooks are - especially in times like these.

We wanted to make you aware that due to COVID-19, we have had government-mandated shut-downs in some of our production facilities and social distancing protocols in others that have reduced our capacity for printing yearbooks. Be assured that everyone who ordered a yearbook will receive one. However, the delivery of your yearbook will be delayed.

It is always our intention to provide you with the very best service and products and we thank you for your patience and understanding. We value the trust you and your school place in us to capture and preserve your important school memories.

Please pass this along to anyone you know who may be interested.

Thank you.

Saludos padres y familiares,
Esta es una encuesta para ayudarnos a planificar el próximo año. A medida que determinamos cómo abrir escuelas, su aporte es extremadamente importante. Es probable que recibamos orientación de los funcionarios de salud del condado de que los estudiantes pueden venir a la escuela por turnos y recibir una combinación de aprendizaje en persona y aprendizaje a distancia. Responda estas preguntas en función de cómo se siente y piensa AHORA, sabiendo que las cosas pueden cambiar. No está haciendo ningún compromiso, solo está retroalimentando. No recopilamos su información personal en esta encuesta.
Gracias

post_text:
Apply to Girls Who Code’s Virtual Summer Immersion Program for an unforgettable summer experience! During this FREE 2-week virtual program, you'll learn the computer science skills you need to make an impact, get an inside look into the tech field, and join a supportive lifelong sisterhood -- all while being virtually hosted by influential companies, like AT&T, Goldman Sachs, Disney, and more.

Current 9th-11th grade girls and non-binary students are eligible to apply. SIP is 100% free and need-based stipends of up to $300 are available for those who qualify to help cover living and tech costs. Low tech? No tech? No problem! Girls Who Code can help you!

Applications are considered on a rolling basis, but classrooms are filling up fast! Apply today at girlswhocode.com/virtualsipform. Completion on a computer is most successful and if you run into any issues you can always email, summerimmersion@girlswhocode.com for support!

post_text:
Due to schools being closed due to COVID-19, children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals can get up to $365 in food benefits
in addition to their pick up meals from school. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT
or P-EBT.

Please share!

With all the changes this Spring, we had to make our ASB Elections strictly online. We had students apply online, interview via ZOOM, and now we are voting electronically. As things changed, these students stepped up!

JSHS ASB/Class Officer Elections will be held this week from Monday May 11th through Friday May 15th at 3pm.

Please vote for the candidate you feel would be representative for our school, and your class. Only one vote is allowed per student. Please encourage other classmates to get out and VOTE! Your voice matters.

Freshman Ballot (Class of 2023)

Sophomore Ballot (Class of 2022)

Junior Ballot (Class of 2021)

Senior Survey: This Senior Survey includes narrowing down the choices for The Class of 2020 Commencement Speaker, a choice of designs for a possible Crew Neck Sweatshirt for the entire Class of 2020.

APP.99PLEDGES.COM
2020 Rodeo Hills PTA Fun Run

Rodeo Hills Elementary
April 23 at 1:03 PM ·

The PTA is sponsoring a VIRTUAL Fun Run on Wednesday, May 13. As a student all you need to do is set a goal for yourself and walk/run on May 13 to raise funds for your school. Your goal can be laps around your block, minutes walking, or if you are inside- running in place. Challenge yourself and let friends and family know your goals!

The PTA uses funds to support student learning including school supplies and student activity accounts, sponsoring family events, and fundraisers. Any and all donations will help support Rodeo Hills and our students.

Please share this link with all your family and friends.

post_text:
Greetings,
This is an outreach message to our local residents and community. The John Swett Unified School District has taken the initiative to install lighting in the pedestrian tunnels between John Swett High School and Carquinez Middle School. We pursued this project in order to address student and community safety concerns about the tunnels being so dark at night. While we are lighting the tunnels at night, this does not mean we want to encourage people to wander through our school grounds. Quite to the contrary. If you see anything improper or questionable going on at one of our schools, please contact the police immediately. It is our goal to be a good community partner and keep everyone safe, especially during these challenging times. If you have any questions, please reach out to me by cell phone at 925-639-7408.
Charles Miller
Superintendent

post_text: A group of John Swett High School students attended the Get Real Academy today!
shared_text:
John Swett High School
March 5 at 4:18 PM ·

Senior girls attended the Get Real Academy today and learned some self-defense techniques, financial literacy, and so much more! Then we had 2 guest speakers: the Director of IT for the FBI and a retired military veteran to be the first woman and first African American leader in its 100-year history. Our girls asked so many great questions and won some gifts in the raffle! They even got to try on a bullet proof jacket for the FBI!
